Revert un-necessary multiplatform architecture

This feature is not useful at the current time, and will likely never be. It adds un-neccessary bloat.

Merge pull request #4 from mrrrgn/require-subparser

Require subparser

Require all cleaners to set up a sub parser in order to run

Without this, all cleaners would run each time cleanslate is called.
This behavior is generally undesirable, so, cleaners may now
set a class variable 'sub_parser_name' to register a sub_parser
which is detected at run time. This ensures that only cleaners
which the user has specified by name are run.
Pass sub_parser object to PlatformCleaner add_argument methods.

Remove dependency on six. A problem with six 1.8 prevents a proper install from setup.py

Restructure the cleanslate project to allow for automatic adaptation across platforms

Cleanslate must support system level operation across many platforms. As a result
it is desirable to be able to define various "cleaner" types, then assign them to a
platform, and have the utility expose any compatible cleaners at runtime.

This makes adding new platform specific cleaners much simpler and mitigates any need
to modify the actual cleanslate.py script in order for them to be surfaced. This
architecture also opens the possibility of a plugin system.

Wait longer before checking if a pid has been killed.

Whitelist processes by command instead of pid

In the event where a process is managed by a service like upstart, and dies,
the pid could change. To prevent cleanslate from killing such processes the
process namd + args should be used for whitelisting.

The number of processes with a given name + arg will still remain the same, i.e. if
the saved process list has three instances of top running in the background only
3 instances of top will be allowed to exist on the next cleanslate run.
